\label{5eg} {\rm \cite[Theorem H, p.344]{egh}}
Let $G$ be a simple group of Lie type in defining characteristic $p>0$, and $g\in G$. Then $g$ is a product of two unipotent elements. Consequently, $e(G)\leq d$, where $d$ is the exponent of 
a Sylow p-subgroup of $G$.

nodes.proof:
Note that $H$ has two conjugacy classes of nontrivial unipotent elements which glue in $\GL_2(q)$, so that a suitable element of $\GL_2(q)$ swaps the two $H$-classes of unipotent elements (see \cite[Lemma 5.2]{TZ04} for a more general fact). So it is enough to prove the result for one of the two classes. Consider the following elements of $H$. 
$$g_1=\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\ -1&2\end{pmatrix}, \hspace{.1cm}
g_2=\begin{pmatrix}2&1\\ -1&0\end{pmatrix}, \hspace{.1cm}
g_3=\begin{pmatrix}1&0\\ -4&1\end{pmatrix}, \hspace{.1cm}
h=\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ -1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}, \hspace{.1cm}
k=\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 1/2 \\ 0 & 1/2 \end{pmatrix}.$$
The characteristic polynomial of $g_1,g_2,g_3$ is $(x-1)^2$, so they are unipotent and $g_1 g_2 g_3=-1$. Moreover $h^{-1}g_1h=g_2$ and $k^{-1}g_1k=g_3$.
